<div id="review_453542269" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/453542269" />
    <a title="Sherri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/427173-sherri"><img alt="Sherri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1631644311p2/427173.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/453542269?book_show_action=true">Nov 11, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sherri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sherri" href="/user/show/427173-sherri">Sherri</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer453542269" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8693060672996468032">Stunned is the only way I can describe my immediate reaction to Let Us Now Praise Famous Men. It is not like any other book I have read and not at all what I expected. (And at times funny in ways I&apos;m pretty sure Agee didn&apos;t mean it to be.) James Agee was 27 when he wrote it. Unbelievable.<br/><br/>I gave it five stars not because I loved every minute of reading it but because of the effort and because of the way he gets across the plight and horror of sharecropping without sentimentality (though with a fa</span>
  <span id="freeText8693060672996468032" style="display:none">Stunned is the only way I can describe my immediate reaction to Let Us Now Praise Famous Men. It is not like any other book I have read and not at all what I expected. (And at times funny in ways I'm pretty sure Agee didn't mean it to be.) James Agee was 27 when he wrote it. Unbelievable.<br /><br />I gave it five stars not because I loved every minute of reading it but because of the effort and because of the way he gets across the plight and horror of sharecropping without sentimentality (though with a fair amount of self-righteousness and some, mmm, bluster I guess for lack of a better word at hand right now).<br /><br />It's probably not for everybody since he has whole chapters of digression and a fairly heavy writing style. It also takes a while to get used to the list-like descriptions, which also take up whole chapters.<br /><br />When you are reading it, it's like swimming a deep, hard-running river. You aren't sure where you are, if you will make it through and if you have the strength. When you finish, you can't believe what a beautiful and amazing river you have just swum across.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8693060672996468032" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


